column168: On June 4, 2023, at 1915 hours, personnel in the CSXT Walbridge, OH Yard discovered a strong odor emitting from CPCX 205191, a residue tank car of Combustible Liquid, N.O.S. The car was isolated and the shipper, Lubrizol, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2023-0605-00294).  EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the odor was emitting from a faulty Vacuum Relief Valve (VRV). The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Joe Eskra (440-364-9372, joe.eskra@lubrizol.com).  Contractor personnel removed the faulty VRV and secured the opening with a pipe plug.  The car was held at the CSX Walbridge yard pending a One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from the FRA.

column168: SequenceEvent: The unprocessed box was found wet in the load area and moved to the hazmat cage for reports. DescribePack: Contents were leaking from under the cap on one of the jugs in the box, even though the cap was on tight.   The label on the box had a 96220302 service code on it. The service code in the system is 96220019.  The contents in the box and the OP-909 are different than HESS.  The contents are actually 100% Reagent Alcohol, (Ethanol Solutions, UN1170, II, Flammable Liquid).  Ftrack has no hazmat information listed.  These items were mentioned in the second ISP entered. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was placed upright in a hazbag lined tote.

SequenceEvent: The package arrived already wet to the station and it was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further containment and inspection. DescribePack: All 4 plastic bottles leaked from loose caps. The bottles have a seal but the caps were not secured. No padding or inner packing materials were used. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon arrival the wet package was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further containment. No release was found.

column168: 1.X-2023060560 SequenceEvent: Package handler found package leaking and called to qa for inspection from trailer# 830244 around 6:30 am. Called to QA. QA retrieved package and inspected. Upon inspection, QA determined it was damages and the package was placed in Hazardous materials bin and placed outside due to ventilation. DescribePack: There were loose caps that leads to leakage of the hazardous materials DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: QA determined it was damages and the package was placed in Hazardous materials bin and placed outside due to ventilation.   2. X-2023060567 SequenceEvent: Package handler found the leaking package and called for QA to inspect package coming from trailer 830244 around 6:37. column168: SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN THE QA AREA. THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF DAMAGE IS UNKNOWN. DescribePack: ONE GLASS BOTTLE IS BROKEN DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: ABSORBENT

SequenceEvent: The package was discovered at Mokena Station 610 on the 200 van line between work areas 216 and 236 by Alpimex BC, Andres Galvez, who immediately informed FedEx Ops Manager, Robert Sanner. During this time, it was discovered that two employees, Darrius Cozart and Jeremy Murray, had come in contact with the hazmat. Robert immediately instructed Darrius and Jeremy to rinse hands under water. Robert then placed damaged hazmat in bag + tote and promptly removed the package from the work area. He then communicated incident to ops admins, Emil Wisch (myself) and Keeli Palmateer.     Emil & Keeli instantly moved to location to assess the incident. There was a small amount of the hazmat spilled in drops under the line/rollers between work areas 216 and 236. There were two places where the spill was more concentrated (one was roughly an area of 10" X 2" and the other roughly 14" x 2"). Emil instructed nearby managers, package handlers, BCs and drivers to stay clear of the area and left to retrieve PPE and cleanup materials while Keeli researched first aid response for Darrius and Jeremy. She echoed Robert's instructions of running contact areas under water (adding the details running under COLD water for 15 MINUTES).    Darrius and Jeremy were moved to the office where Senior Manager, Nancy Morris and P&D Manager, Patryk Rojewski took over first aid.    Emil returned and spread AMPHOMAG neutralizer on spill locations while Keeli observed (training).    It was later discovered that the spill had actually originated in a trailer in the unload. It is unknown how the damage to the package occurred. There were no reports of any injuries to any employees who were near that trailer at the time the package was unloaded. Emil and Keeli moved to the location where the spill had originated. Emil spread AMPHOMAG neutralizer on all visible locations of the spilled hazmat while Keeli observed (training).    Emil and Keeli later returned to both locations where the neutralizer was spread and collected all materials in hazmat bags and totes.    There are no known complications to employees, Darrius Cozart or Jeremy Murray, proceeding the incident up to the time of this report. Both reported to work the following day with no known restrictions. DescribePack: There was a large hole/tear in the outer container of the package. Inside the package were 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottles of hazmat. Each bottle was contained in a plastic bag. One of those bottles' caps was unfastened. No damage DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: 1 hour is overestimating. I believe the release was less than 30 minutes (in our facility, station 610). Response was timely and well-coordinated. Mitigation included prompt first-aid to 2 affected employees, near-instant containment of damaged package allowing no future release and neutralization of acid to prevent any further damage to people, package and facility.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XAQ experienced a UN3264 Reaxis S 50 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons of product released to an 8' x 15' area of the trailer floor and to the asphalt lot below due to a pallet puncture. The product was transferred into a new tote. Soda ash and absorbents were utilized to clean the impacted areas along with other impacted freight. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized. All waste was placed into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2.5ft-by-2.5ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that thirty (30) pounds of material was released due to a load shift  during  transit  damaging  one  (1)  poly  pail  causing  the  lid  to  come  off.  First  Call  Environmental personnel  moved all the  poly pails from the pallet to verify only  one (1)  pail was damaged and then swept up the released material. The non-damaged pails were restacked on to two pallets and shipped onto the consignee. The damaged poly pail was placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum along with the  recovered  released  material  and  was  staged  onsite  at  the  terminal  prior  to  the  contractor demobilizing.  The  generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  for  the  ESTES  DGRM  team  to  coordinate disposal.

column168: The 4 5 gal. Poly Jerry Cans were placed on a pallet and not secured what so ever. A single plastic Jerry Can fell over while in-transit allowing 2.5 Gal. of the material to be released to the trailer floor from the removable screw on cap.
column169: The facility where this material was loaded and the driver transporting this material will receive coaching regarding proper load securement. The driver responsible for this load will receive a written disciplinary and will complete remedial training regarding proper load inspection and load securement.

column168: On June 1, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of nickel sulfate (UN3082) was damaged due to a load shift and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer floor and concrete surface below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES&H services (ESH) to remediate the site. ESH personnel deployed granular absorbents and worked them in using hand tools as well as utilizing degreasing agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product. The crew overpacked the damaged 275-gallon tote into one (1) 330-gallon tote and all nickel sulfate impacted material in five (5) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

On June 1, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN3266 were damaged during a load shift and released approximately five (5) gallons to the trailer interior. R&L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to assess and remediate the site. HES personnel deployed granular absorbents and absorbent pads to the impacted trailer and swept them in using hand tools. All spent absorbents were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon poly drum for disposal.

column168: On 06-08-2023 a CN Mechanical employee observed liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve of rail car # HSRX 3393 while performing an inbound train inspection at the CN Waterloo Yard in Waterloo, Iowa. The employee notified the CN Yard Coordinator who in turn made the proper notifications to all departments.  CN Dangerous Goods Officer upon arrival and inspection found the bottom outlet valve cap to be less than tool tight and the bottom outlet valve handle to not be in the fully closed position, allowing product to enter the cap and leak out.  The bottom outlet valve was moved to the fully closed position. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench.  Rail car was released back to CN transportation for continued movement to destination.

column168: The 55 gallon drum in temporary storage at Veolia's PA 10-day intransit facility when it suddenly reacted, causing the drum to rupture. All of the contents of the drum release from the drum into secondary containment in the waste storage area.  While there were employees that were nearby when this occurred, there were no injuries and no exposures.  The pH of the liquid was tested and was found to be between 12 and 13.  This was the only drum in the shipment. Veolia contacted a third party emergency response company to clean up the spill and decontaminate the area.
column169: Veolia will verify with Johns Hopkins that they are classifying the hazardous waste properly. In the future, waste shipments from this generator will be shipped with vented bung caps in place. Shipments from this customer should not occur until a 24 hour waiting period has passed after a container has been filled and closed. Drums displaying any signs of pressure build up will be vented prior to transportation.

column168: Environmental Works was dispatched to the site. Upon  the  contractor’s  arrival,  personnel  observed  that the  released  material  impacted  an  8ft-by-10ft area  of  the  trailer  floor  and  estimated  that  two  (2)  gallons  of  material  was  released  due  to  a  nail damaging the bottom of one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. Environmental Works personnel removed all the cargo from the trailer and transferred the non-damaged drums to a new pallet due to heavy impact to the original pallet by the released material. The impacted pallet was cut up and placed into two (2) 55- gallon poly drums. Environmental Works personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area of the trailer floor and neutralized the trailer floor. Environmental Works personnel confirmed the area was  neutralized  with  a  pH  strip.  The  spent  absorbents  and  neutralizers  were  gathered  and containerized into the two (2) 55-gallon poly drums along with the cut-up pallet. The damaged 55-gallon poly drum was overpacked into one (1) 95-gallon poly drum was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

QA responded by removing pkg from trailer, transferring pkg into HazMat tote for further handling. DescribePack: Bottle lid seemed to have loosened enough to cause liquid to leak out. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Once pkg was noticed to be leaking package handlers notified QA to come and contain leaking pkg from trailer.

SequenceEvent: Pkg was found while unloading and was leaking, at about 14:30. Completed containment and started processing Hazmat per FEDEX policies and proceedures. DescribePack: The seam of both plastic bottles failed at the same location on the body of the plastic jug behind the handle. Note: The fiberboard box is designed for four like size jugs and only two shipped and paper was placed in open void. There was an insert at the neck of the bottles to prevent movement. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Hazmat liner, tote w/ lid, all containment material were quickly performed and moved to Q/A.

SequenceEvent: Box was already inside the HazMat Cage during morning audit.  Someone had already scanned it a 39 and put it inside the Cage.  I put it in a red tote and HazMat bag. DescribePack: The top and side of box was wet.  One cap was loose within the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: I put it in a red tote and HazMat bag.  Someone before myself had already moved it to the HazMat Cage on a pallet.

column43: ( hydrogen peroxide and nitric acid, stabilized)
column168: SequenceEvent: Handlers were unloading trailer, and the package was an unmarked hazmat. As a package handler was reaching for another package that fell and hit the unmarked hazmat knocking it to the floor. This caused the top of the pail to come loose, and the contents leaked out of the package. This occurred around 5am. DescribePack: The top of the package came loose. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: QA was called for clean up, and the belts were stopped for the station. Gloves, litter,  and n95 masks were used during clean up. Handlers were removed from trailer, and n95s were given to handlers nearby. The doors were opened, and the fans were turned on.

SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND COMPLETELY DESTROYED.  THE SIDES WAS ABSORBED FROM THE LEAKAGE THROUGHOUT THE CARDBOARD BOX. DescribePack: THE CAP INSIDE THE PACKAGE WAS SLIGHLY NOT ON THE CONTAINER. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY HANDLED USING THE CORRECT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS NEEDED FOR THE SPILL.

SequenceEvent: The package was found leaking. It was immediately placed in a Hazmat container to minimize the spillage. DescribePack: The package was wet and leaking. The side of the fiberboard box was soaked and ripped. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: As soon as the package was noticed to be leaking, it was immediately placed in a Hazmat container so that the spill would be limited.
SequenceEvent: Package found wet and leaking on bottom of box. DescribePack: 1 gallon bottle cap loose. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Leaked some liquid.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: SequenceEvent: PACKAGE WAS REMOVE FROM UNLOAD TRAILER BY AN MANAGER PUT ON A CART THEN BROUGHT TO HAZMAT CAGE DescribePack: CAPS LOOSENED AND SEALS FAILED NO HOLES OR CRACKS DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PUT IN TO A HAZMAT TOTE WITH BAG

SequenceEvent: OPS manager noticed wet hazmat, QA was notified. DescribePack: Due to loose cap, contents spilled and outer box became wet. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: OPS Admin QA placed wet hazmat package in plastic lined hazmat tote while wearing latex gloves.

SequenceEvent: Package was found wet on the QA work area. Package was stood upright and placed in a bag. DescribePack: Crushed tops of bottle. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was stood upright and caps and bottles secured.

SequenceEvent: found on unloadside by QA.package was taken to hazmat cage for processing. DescribePack: Loose closure points on two of the four bottles causing leaking DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: put hazmat in savage drum and transported it safely to hazmat cage

SequenceEvent: QA was notified of a leaking hazmat and package was secured in a salvage drum. DescribePack: Upon inspection, one bottle of degreaser had a loose cap and was leaking. Soiling this package in the process. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Closures were tightened to insure no more liquid could leak out.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: SequenceEvent: PACKAGE LEFT AT HAZMAT DescribePack: BENT AT SEAM AROUND BOTTOM OF CAN CAUSING LEAK DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE WAS PUT IN A LINED HAZMAT TOTE AND PLACED ON CONTAINMENT PALLET

SequenceEvent: Package found to be leaking. Placed in to spill bin and brought to QA cage for further processing. DescribePack: Cap loosened on one bottle allowing liquid to leak out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Placed into spill bin to minimize further leakage elsewhere.

SequenceEvent: Package was found leaking on van line 10 and placed on hazmat pallet. DescribePack: 1 out of 4 jugs of condenser coil cleaner had a loose cap and leaked. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Sort manager notified QA about the damage, and it was brought to the hazmat cage.
SequenceEvent: arrived wet do to loose caps. tightened up caps DescribePack: loose caps DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: tightened up caps

SequenceEvent: The package was found on the unload dock wet from an internal leakage. DescribePack: 1 of 2 Jugs of Zep Industrial purple degreaser with its cap removed which caused the spillage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Absorbent pads and powder was used to clean the effected area.
SequenceEvent: Arrived wet do to loose cap. Tightened up cap. DescribePack: loose cap DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Tightened up cap

SequenceEvent: Package was retrieved after it was called out by a manager DescribePack: the liquid leaked through a loose cap. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the spill was cleaned with absorb-all and the leaker was placed in a tote with a liner.

SequenceEvent: Package was found inside drivers van, with the code 10 (INSPECTION REQUIRED) applied to package. Package was found separated from other packages, behind the drivers seating area, on the floor. DescribePack: 2 caps were loose on the bottles, causing the liquid from inside to leak out. DurationRel: 6 and MitigateEffect: Package was pulled and placed in the hazmat cage, near the ventilation fan. During the inspection of the package, the caps were sealed back on securely.

DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: the box was bagged and placed into a hazbag lined tote.

SequenceEvent: Box was found in a plastic bag in a carrying tote in the QA damage area and moved to Hazmat processing area for inspection. DescribePack: Upon inspection, cap on plastic container could be tightened with a small twist.  Container was still mostly full.  Box was wet near top side of container. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: Leakage was not spreading.  Package was placed in a salvage drum during inspection.

column168: SequenceEvent: Box was found in the load side with the top corners of the box wet. The box was placed in a red hazardous bin with 1 layer of absorbent, a hazardous materials bag, and another layer of absorbent. DescribePack: Box was found stained from the outer top corners. Upon inspection the inner top flaps of the box were found stained and a little bit of the corners. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The spillage was not actively leaking so only 1 sheet of absorbent was used to cover that part of the box. It was then placed in a bin layered with absorbent and a hazardous materials bag.

SequenceEvent: Package found in unload during OTP, leaking. Placed in tote. DescribePack: 1 bottle has a crack in the lid, all bottles dented and leaking contents. Brown fiberboard box packaged over usual 3 pack box. No transport labels on outside package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Placed in tote.

SequenceEvent: BOX LEFT OUTSIDE OF HWPA. DescribePack: BOX WET AND TORN ON OPPOSITE SIDES. INSIDE, 2 PF THE 4 BOTTLES LEAKING. ONE BOTTLE HAD A GROSSLY MISALLIGNED CAP AND BROKEN SEAL. THE OTHER BOTTLE'S SEAL HAD A SMALL HOLE AND SLIGHTLY MISALLIGNED CAP. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: THE CAPS WERE SCREWED ON PROPERLY AND THE BOTTLES AND BOX WERE PLACED IN A LINED SALVAGE DRUM.

column168: SequenceEvent: BOX WAS FOUND LEAKING ON UNLOAD ROLLERS. BOX WAS BROUGHT TO THE HWPA IN A LINED RED TOTE BY HAZMAT ADMIN. DescribePack: BOX WET UP ONE SIDE. INSIDE, 1 BOTTLE VERY MISALLIGNED CAP, NO SEAL. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: CAP WAS CORRECTED AND TIGHTENED. BOTTLES AND BOX PLACED IN A LINED SALVAGE DRUM.

SequenceEvent: SMELLY WET PACKAGE WAS FOUND DURING THE UNLOAD PUT IN A HAZMAT TOTE AND BROUGHT OVER FOR INSPECTION. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND TO BE A DAMAGED HAZMAT AND THE HAZMAT PROCESS WAS STARTED. DescribePack: LOOSE CAP WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: BOX WAS TURNED RIGHT SIDE UP PUT IN A HAZMAT TOTE AND BROUGHT OVER TO THE OVER HEAD VENT IN THE HAZMAT CAGE.

SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LOADED ON A TUGGER CART INCORRECTLY, AS IT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE, INSTEAD OF UPRIGHT.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE EXTERIOR WAS DAMP AND LEAKING.  WHEN I HANDLED THE PACKAGE, IT WAS LEAKING A PINKISH LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM.  UPON INSPECTION, THE PLASTIC CAP WAS FOUND THREADED INCORRECTLY AND NOT SEALED COMPLETELY. DescribePack: THE EXTERIOR WAS NOT FAULTY.  THE PLASTIC CAP THAT WAS MEANT TO BE SEALED PROPERLY, WAS NOT ON CORRECTLY.  THE PLASTIC CAP WAS THREADED IMPROPERLY, LEAVING ROOM FOR THE INNER LIQUID TO SEEP OUT IF HANDLED THE WRONG WAY. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO AN UPRIGHT POSITION AND MOVED TO A SECURE AREA.

column168: Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area of the tote top and estimated that one (1) ounce of material was released due to a faulty cap on top of the 275- gallon poly tote. Enviroserve personnel neutralized the released material and replaced the faulty cap with a new cap and gasket. The DOT officer approved the work performed. The neutralized material, along  with  impacted  rags  and  the  damaged  cap  were  containerized  into  one  (1)  5-gallon  poly  pail. Enviroserve  personnel  transported  the  generated  waste  offsite  for  proper  disposal.  The  generated waste will remain onsite at the contractor’s location for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: On 6/9/2023 at approximately 1330, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 3724286 at the sort facility in Olive Branch, reporting an undeclared compressed gas cylinder.  The shipment consisted of 15 fiberboard boxes, all containing various diving accessoeries.  Due to lost paperwork, 3 of the packages were rerouted to the package research and recovery facility where further research revealed a compressed gas cylinder in one of the 3 packages. There were two black cylinders and 1 silver cylinder.  This pacakge was prepared in accoradance with the IATA Regulations.   The other 12 shipments appeared to move on in transit.  The 3 packages are being held, pending an FAA investigation.

This package (772418606624) was found while unloading a PM Express shuttle from the FedEx Ground facility in Willmar, MN.  The courier suspected this package was DG due to the markings on the box calling in herbicide and being in UN spec packaging.  He brought it to manager Wayne Peterson's attention before the truck was offloaded.  The manager inspected the package and looked up the SDS online to verify transportation information.  In section 14 this chemical is listed as IATA regulated for air transport, as a UN 3082.  As the  package contained 2 inner containers, both containing 2.5 Gallons (9.45 L) this package would not qualify for shipment under special provision 197.  It should be noted according to the SDS this package would not be regulated if it were to solely travel via truck.  Package was instructed to be bumped by the Express station and to contact the FedEx Ground Facility it came from and have them retrieve the package.  A second identical package was (772418607561) discovered later that night and was give n the same disposition.

column168: On 6/02/2023 Veolia employees were loading a truck at Moderna when an a one gallon pail fell over and started to leak. The driver immediately picked up the pail to stop the leak. Upon inspection the employee identified that a material leaked out of the pail because there was no vermiculite in the pail as required for a proper lab pack. One of the inner containers of hydrogen peroxide leaked when it fell over and then leaked out of the outer container. About 100 milliters of hydrogen peroxide leaked out of the container.   The spill was cleaned up and absorbent was placed within the pail and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. The pail leaked about 100 milliters of a class 5.1(8) Oxidizing, corrosive liquid hydrogen peroxide solution. The liquid was cleaned up with absorbent and absorbent was added to the pail as required. The duration of release was less than 1 minute.
column169: On 6/02/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation is the inner containers in the pail were not packaged correctly and did not have sufficient absorbent around them. Retraining of employees will be performed.

column168: Traveling southwest on KY-38, MM24-25, Tractor and Trailer dropped off narrow berm of road and rolled over embankment into creek. The rollover resulted in rupturing the shell of the trailer and releasing approximately 113 bbls. of crude oil into ditch/creek. A rock in the creek is believed to be what punctured the shell of the aluminum trailer.  Kentucky Emergency Response Branch as well as Kentucky Department of Environmental Protection were notified immediately. Contract Spill Response/Cleanup company (EcoTech Environmental USA) was contacted with a response time of roughly two hours. Onsite EMS services responded by inserting a wooden wedge plug into the shell of trailer along with a putty sealant to slow the leakage of product.  Kentucky Emergency Management Report #20232450 Kentucky Department of Environmental Protection #2518189
column169: Ergon Trucking Inc. will utilize this incident as a High Level Learning Event with current and future drivers.

column168: On June 13, 2023, three (3) 25-pound bags of low temp salt oxidizer were damaged by improper shipper handling and released approximately five (5) pounds of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted surface. TLE personnel deployed granular absorbent pads, degreaser, and hepa vac to the red pigment-impacted trailer interior and collected them. All spent absorbent pads and vac liner were collected and containerized into one (1) 15-gallon drum and one (1) 35-gallon drum for terminal disposal.

column168: While unloading a truck at Veolia's ten day intransit facility in Phoenix, AZ, Veolia employees observed a 275 gallon tote to be leaking. Further investigation revealed there was corrosion to the floor pan of the tote that rusted enough to create a sharp edge. The sharp edge punctured the bottom of the tote's bladder resulting in a release of material from the tote. The contents of the tote were transferred to a new tote for continued transportation. Spill pads were used by Veolia personnel to cleanup the released material. It is believed that the corrosion was likely due to the tote being staged/stored outside at the shipper's location.
column169: The shipper will be reminded to store containers inside or under cover while pending disposal.

column168: On June 13, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1170 was punctured and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to remediate the impacted surface. Crews observed the leaking 55-gallon drum had been placed on its side to prevent any further leaking. One (1) gallon of ethanol solution was estimated to have released to the dock floor. AS personnel deployed granular absorbents to the ethanol solution-impacted dock floor and swept them in with hand tools. The leaking 55-gallon drum and the collected spent absorbents were containerized into one (1) 95-gallon overpack. This overpack was labeled with a "hazardous" label and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

To be clear, there was nothing wrong with the valves on our trailer, I just didn't know what to flag on number 25.  That said our driver hooked up to the right fill line at the customer (nitric acid) but then when he turned around to our trailer he ended up to the wrong compartment which contained sodium hydroxide.  He admits that he didn't do a final check like they are trained to do.  When he started to unload smoke quickly formed from the customer tank.    He shut down.  The reaction caused approximately 10 gallons to leak on to the concrete floor.  A clean up crew was hired to come in and clean up the floor and empty the tank when the reaction subsided.
column169: Our driver did not follow company policies or training in this situation.  Due to the severity we have severed employment ties with the employee.  Additional fleet training is taking place so that other drivers on the account understand what can happen if the process and training are not followed.

column168: A semi tractor was driving northbound on the Dalton Highway around Mile 126, approaching a curve that is colloquially referred to among Alaskan truck drivers as "Oh Shit Corner".  The driver entered the corner at excessive speed, and immediately before the corner struck a large pothole in the road, which apparently caused two trailer tires to blow out, contributing to the loss of control in the corner.  The tractor trailer combination rolled onto its side and departed the roadway, coming to rest beside and below the highway grade.  The driver received only minor injuries and did not require transport for medical attention.  At the time of the initial response, Alaska Commercial Vehicle Compliance and Alaska State Troopers believed there may have been a release due to the odor, however Suburban Propane (shipper) personnel arrived on the scene and reported there was no leak beyond normal vent operation.  Personnel and equipment were mobilized to the scene, the product was transloaded into another tanker, and a wrecker removed the tractor and trailer and brought them back to Fairbanks.  Professional traffic control allowed this to be completed without requiring a road closure.
column169: In training for commercial drivers, emphasize the handling effects of cargo tanks and other top-heavy loads, and the propensity for rollovers.  A lot of training material on this subject emphasizes slowing down on highway on and off ramps; while nationwide this is probably the greatest exposure for cargo tank rollovers, the way the topic is presented may not resonate as well with drivers on rural and mountain roads who face the same challenges in terms of road geometry and the need to properly manage their speed.

column168: A Memphis spill agent was called to the Dangerous Goods building for a leaking package. Upon arrival the agent was told that the fiberboard box fell off the rollers and struck the edge of the catwalk. This punctured the fiberboard box and one of the two metal jerrycans inside. The jerrycans were packaged with Styrofoam molding for bracing and bubble wrap for dunnage. Each jerrycan was enclosed in a single plastic bag sealed with a bag tie. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper was contacted for an amended declaration for movement.

column168: While offloading a straight truck at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI, a 15 gallon steel drum fell over. As the drum fell, the contents of the drum shifted and created a spark which resulted in the lid shooting off. The Veolia employees offloading the truck witnessed a ball of light come from the drum. Upon inspection, it was discovered that the drum contained multiple lead acid batteries which were not protected from short circuiting as well as two luminous tube transformers. This incident resulted in a vapor release only, due to pressure build up with the drum.  No amount hazard material was released as a result of the incident.
column169: Veolia employees were reminded to inspect the inner contents of battery drums prior to shipment. If the inspection was performed they would have noticed the batteries were packaged improperly as well as the two transformers. The offeror will also be reminded that batteries should always be the only hazardous material contained in a package and they must be prepared in a manner that will prevent short circuits and protect the battery terminals. The transformers should have been packaged separately.

column168: On June 30, 2023, at 0400 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal LSL experienced a UN3264 “Sure Klean 600” release from a 5-gallon poly jug due to a pallet puncture impacting the trailer floor and concrete lot below. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct all on site cleanup operations. On June 30, 2023, at 0723 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately all 5-gallons of product released from the jug impacting an 8’ x 20’ area of the trailer floor and concrete lot below. Absorbents and soda ash were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. Three impacted pallets were cut up and containerized along with the empty jug and impacted absorbents. The waste was placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums and then staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: The package was sent up the van line belt to be loaded into a truck. A package handler noticed it was wet and informed QA. QA isolated the wet box at the end of the belt and inspected it for leakage. It was discovered that the cap was loose on the plastic bottle inside of the box, resulting in minimal spillage. The majority was absorbed by the cardboard box, with a small amount leaking onto the walkway of the belt itself. An absorb pad was put down to soak up the spill. DescribePack: The cap was loose on the bottle. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Minimal spillage occurred on the van line and absorb pads were put in place to soak up the liquid.

SequenceEvent: Package was moved to the rollers to be loaded onto the trailer.  The package fell from that height causing the break. Leak was contained using a spill absorber/neutralizer. SequenceEvent: The package was found to be leaking by a package handler on the load Side. He then informed management who then relayed the message to me. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: I isolated the package and placed into a Hazardous bucket. Then proceeded to take the package to the Hazmat cage. Once in the cage the contents were placed into a barrel.

column168: RESPONDER RESPONDED TO UNLOAD DOOR, WORE REQUIRED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE), FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, CLEANED UP AND REMOVED TO DMP.

The truck and trailer hauling a water tank and agricultural sprayer was traveling south on a county gravel road 47th Ave. SW,  9.5 miles north of Hwy 21. Driver met an oncoming pickup truck, slowed down to 10 miles per hour  and moved over to make room to pass the oncoming vehicle.  The trailer wheels were pulled into the ditch as the soft shoulder of the gravel road gave way. As the driver continued forward the trailer pulled the truck drive wheels into the ditch and at this moment the truck and trailer tipped over. The IBC of the ag pesticide WideARmatch that was inside the secured carrier on the trailer deck flipped over and the product that was inside the IBC flowed out the 1-1/2 inch vent hole cap that is located on top of the IBC and it was in an open position to vent.  That product spilled onto the ground and the release was about 10 minutes. Some product soaked into the ground and floor dry was placed on the remaining liquid pooled up under the shuttle.
column169: Training was provided to company drivers reviewing the possible dangers of driving to close to the shoulder of the road.  -Soft shoulder will give way to the weight of the transport truck and trailer. -This equipment has a high center of gravity and is prone to tipping over. -Additional anchor straps will be added to keep the IBC from flipping over.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN2289 718 I - Carboline CM 847 release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 240-gallons of product released to the trailer floor and multiple areas of the concrete lot below due to the tote being puncture by a loading bar. A skid steer was utilized to work sand and absorbents into the impacted areas. Citric acid was also deployed to neutralize the impacted areas. All impacted absorbents, the damaged tote, and two 55-gallon poly drums of impacted absorbents were staged into a roll off onsite pending disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal XKO experienced a UN1760 Eggs So Clean pH Booster release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-gallons of product released to a 10' x 50' area of the trailer floor and concrete lot below due to a trailer wall hook puncture. The material was transferred into a new tote. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas along with citric acid to neutralize the material. The damaged tote was then cup up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal LGT experienced a UN3262 DS-88 Alkaline Cleaner release from a 5-gallon poly pail. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-pound of product released to a 2' x 2' area of the trailer floor due to improper loading/load shift. The damaged pail and released product were collected along with all cleanup debris into a 30-gallon and 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 6/20/2023 a Veolia employee from the Schenectady, NY office was loading drums from a trailer into another trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY ten day intransit facility when the employee clipped a 55-gallon steel drum with the corner of a pallet while placing it in an outbound trailer. The leak occurred when the employee was loading drums into the trailer and the employee misjudged how close the pallet was to the drums that were already in the trailer for shipment. The 55 gallon drum containing flammable liquids was mostly dented but a small crease caused a leak from the drum and about a liter leaked out of the impacted drum. Liquid was only observed on trailer right below drum and did not leak out of the vehicle.   The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum, the spill cleaned up, and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. The drum leaked about 1 liter of a class 3 flammable liquid solution. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the lid on the drum was overpacked properly to prevent it from spilling. The duration of release is anticipated to be less than 1 minute as the employee noticed the accident right away and an estimated 1 liter of flammable liquids leaked.
column169: On 6/20/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation is the employee misjudged the distance from the corner of the pallet to the nearby drum that was hit. The employee was removed from the forklift and retrained. The employee and safety manager had a face to face meeting to discuss the incident.

column168: Our transport driver was Southbound on K14 when it left the roadway to the West and then corrected back onto the roadway. Our transport driver then over-corrected and entered the West ditch again. The vehicle overturned and came to rest on its driver's side facing South. The tanker trailer was breached upon impact causing the contents (Ethanol) to leak out. The incident took place at 12:11pm. The roadway was shut down by Kansas Highway Patrol when they arrived at the scene around 12:30pm. Sedgwick County HAZ-Mat Response Team was was dispatched to mitigate the effects of the release. The Ethanol was released into the soil, which was dug up by our remediation crew over the following days. The K14 was opened back up at 7:30pm when the transport and trailer were towed away.
column169: -Driver responsible for the spill was terminated.  -Training over the incident was and will be discussed in upcoming (2023) Safety Meetings with all CRCT Drivers.

column168: While loading an IBC into a trailer, forklift operator did not realize the forkblades from his forklift were protruding from it and as a result the forkblades hit and punctured another IBC already staged in the trailer consequently contributing to the unintentional release. Immediate containment procedures were put in place by Level III Hazwoper employees. Local authorities and a local third party spill response company were contacted. The VT State Hazmat Team responded as did our third party spill responder company. Spilled material was contained, neutralized, and cleaned up with various absorbents which were placed into various recovery containers. The remaining product that was still in IBC was neutralized and pumped out and placed into a recovery container. The punctured IBC was cut up and placed into recovery containers for proper disposal.
column169: Forklift operators need to be aware of the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to help prevent  these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: On June 19, 2023, at 0722 ET, an XPO Logistics tractor trailer (truck # 5322228, trailer #321-6811) was involved in a rollover accident when traveling down Interstate 40 eastbound. As a result of the accident, non-regulated “FM-9058 IBCQ” and UN1263 “Thermo Sorb VOC” released impacting the asphalt and soil shoulder as well as into the ditch. No storm drains or waterways were impacted by the release. At 1120 ET, XPO Logistics retained Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage and oversee the above referenced incident. ARTG Environmental was secured to perform all onsite cleanup and remediation activities. At 1315 ET, ARTG personnel arrived onsite to conduct an initial site assessment. Billy’s Wrecker service was also onsite and towed the damaged unit along with the damaged cargo to their yard. ARTG secured the impacted soil and roadside area with boom and departed site to head to the wrecker yard. Once the contractors arrived at the wrecker yard, poly sheeting was utilized to secure the damaged trailer while awaiting the arrival of a relief trailer. The crew departed site for the day.  On June 20 and 21, 2023, ARTG personnel returned to the spill site to complete the excavation. The crew advised the product released had traveled down and embankment in 10” tall grass but did not reach a nearby creek which was approximately 15’ away. The crew dug approximately 1’ deep into the ditch due to woodchip material being in the ditch, allowing for a more porous surface. The impacted shoulder measured approximately 250' x 4' leading into a slope measuring approximately 60' x 30' which led into the ditch in an 80' x 6' area. A total of approximately 270-tons of impacted soil was excavated and staged roadside, secured with poly sheeting awaiting disposal.   On June 23, 2023, ARTG returned to the tow yard to complete the trailer cleanout. All unimpacted freight was offloaded into a relief trailer. The contractors were able to confirm during this cleanup what material was released to the roadside. Approximately 500-gallons of non-regulated FM-9058 released from (2) 275-gallon poly totes as well as approximately 40-gallons of UN1263 “Thermo-Sorb VOC” released from (8) 5-gallon metal pails. The damaged pails of paint were containerized into (2) 55-gallon metal drums which were transported to the XPO terminal located 6101 Lindsey Rd, Little Rock, AR 72206, for terminal personnel to manage. The two totes are staged at ARTG’s shop pending disposal.  On July 11, 2023, ARTG returned to the site to take confirmation samples for site closure, lab results are still pending.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 06/23/2023, at 1332 hours, personnel in the CSXT Grafton Yard discovered TILX 198280, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, West Virginia DEP, and National Response Center were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2023-0623-00192). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the reclosing pressure relief device stuck in the open position that resulted in the release of lading while the car was in motion. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ms. Judy Watson of Valero Marketing, phone (210) 241-2886, email judy.watson@valero.com. Contractor personnel manually reset the pressure relief device. The contents of the car were transloaded without incident, and the car will move to a shop of the car owner's choice with an OTMA-1 per 49 CFR 174.50. (FRA assigned Investigators have been updated) The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 422 NARRI: 32

column168: Driver arrived at customer location for a waste pickup.  Upon opening the trailer door the driver discovered that the trailer floor was wet and smelled strong odor.  Driver immediately called dispatch and placed spill pads and speedy dry to contain the liquid to the trailer.  Management called for emergency response to respond.  Response time was 2-3 hours.  Driver stayed with the vehicle until the response crew arrived and material was transferred into another 5 gallon drum.  Original drum was placed in an overpack along with any cleanup materials that were used.    Cause of the failure was determined to be missing gasket and ring for drum was put on upside down.  In addition to the missing gasket there was a pinhole discovered in the side of the drum where the drum had been picked for loading.

1. X-2023070593 SequenceEvent: Item arrived to facility damaged. QA was notified and immediately took action. QA responded with both a bucket and red bag to placed damaged item into. Item was then brought back to hazmat cage where it was processed and handled according to guidelines. DescribePack: Package had loose caps which caused interior leakage. Spillage was not much however, it was enough to cause damage to the exterior of package as well as interior contents. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package caps were tightened and placed in red bag to prevent further spillage.   2. X-2023070594 SequenceEvent: Upon arrival to facility, package was damaged. QA was called to unload are to assist in removing items. Once there, the package was placed inside a red bag and then added to a container. QA brought the tote with container over to the hazmat cage where the item was then dealt with accordingly. HESS, 105 & 39 as well as DPR and ISR was completed on package. DescribePack: Package contained bottles that had loose caps. The loose caps caused the liquid to spill our of the plastic bottles and into the box. In return, the exterior package was also damaged. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Items were placed in a plastic tote and contained within a red bag. This helped prevent any further leakage.  3. X-2023070595 SequenceEvent: Package was leaking upon arrival. QA was notified and immediately responded to area where package was located. Item was then placed into a bag that was then placed into a tote and brought back to hazmat location. Item was handled accordingly. DPR, ISF, and HESS reports were done on this package. DescribePack: Package contained two plastic both of which contained 44oz. of disinfectant. Both bottles had loose caps that caused the bottles to leak into the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Once package was picked up from unload area, it was placed into a tote that was then brought to QA location and processed according to standards.

column168: SequenceEvent: Admin discovered a leaking package in a UNPOP Y-rated fiberboard box with product label on the side and a faded but not illegible barcode; no diamond label or proper shipping name marked. The package was found on the HMPA staging pallet. When attempting to decipher the barcode via DTL, ten other potential undeclared hazmats were found in the shipment. Due to being unable to trap the packages or strip the trailer, SALT (the next destination) was notified of the incoming Undeclared hazmats. DescribePack: One of four 3.78 liter plastic bottles lost 2.6L of fluid due to a loose cap closure and minor denting. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Class 3 Spill PPE was donned, the SDS was consulted, and ventilation was utilized.

SequenceEvent: Package was found when unloading a van. Package was wet and leaking. Package was removed from operation area and taken to Hazmat Cage for processing. Any spill was cleaned up and materials used were brought to Hazmat cage. SequenceEvent: The hazardous material drum was inspected and processed by the QA team. It was then put onto a tugger cart to be taken to a trailer to be loaded. When the bucket was placed on to the tugger cart and started travelling, the liquid inside of the drum started to leak out of the top seal. When the tugger operator reached the load end, he notified management. The liquid got on the tugger cart and on the outside of the drum. No physical contact was made with the liquid by any employees. DescribePack: The lid to the drum did not fit correctly or was improperly sealed. No visible damage to the cap/outer container was found. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The drum was immediately set on to a flat stable surface away from the operation to prevent any further spillage.

column168: SequenceEvent: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER LEAKING, THIS WAS THEN REPORTED IMMEDIATELY TO THE OPERATION MANAGER RUNNING UNLOAD. THAT INFORMATION WAS RELAYED TO THE QUALITY ASSURANE TEAM WHERE THEY USED PROPER SAFETY EQUIPMENT TO PICKUP HAZMAT & PUT INTO YELLOW HAZMAT DRUM. THEN USED THE SOAKING AGENT POWDER TO SOAK UP LEAKAGE AND CLEAN AREA. DescribePack: BOX WAS TORN OPEN BY CORROSIVE LEAKAGE FROM BOTTLES THAT HAD LOOSE CAPS. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: QUALITY ASSURANE USED PROPER SAFETY EQUIPMENT TO PICKUP HAZMAT & PUT INTO YELLOW HAZMAT DRUM. THEN USED THE SOAKING AGENT POWDER TO SOAK UP LEAKAGE AND CLEAN AREA OF CORROSIVE LIQUID.

SequenceEvent: We opened the trailer door and upon doing so we saw the hazmat with a wet spot and foam on the side of the box. Upon seeing it we prepared ourselves to handle the hazmat by ensuring no one came over until it was cleaned up, we got the correct PPE gear to handle the small spill and placed everything into a yellow drum with a hazmat bag inside. DescribePack: The failure to the package was the lid not being secure and the liquid had leaked only on one side of the package which caused the whole side of the box to become open including the inner box that the 4-gallon hazardous items were located in. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: we quickly and effectively gathered a yellow drum to place the hazmat as to not allow it to damage any packages and place absorbent to ensure everything was clean and ready for use.

column168: The driver picked up a load of Industrial Motive Power Batteries from a customer in Dayton, NJ. The batteries looked to be secured to the pallets and the pallets looked to be in good, sturdy condition. The driver traveled about 2 miles down the road to a stop light. While pulling away from the light he heard a bang coming from his trailer. He pulled over as soon as he found a safe place to do so along a ramp going onto the Turnpike. When he opened the trailer to check the load he saw that one of the batteries had fallen over due to a pallet collapsing. THere was no harsh braking, acceleration or cornering events to trigger the spill. He then checked the rest of the load and saw that there were other pallets that were not looking as stable as they should be. The driver did have some soda ash on his truck which he used to soak up, neutralize and berm as much of the spilled acid as he could. He did call back to Corporate for help with the clean up. The police showed up to the scene. After assessing the spill and seeing that the trailer is no longer leaking the police assisted the driver to tum his truck around and off the Turnpike ramp for easier assistance for clean up. The Hazmat clean up team arrived shorlty after the turnaround. While wating for the Hazmat clean up team, the driver contacted the cutomer that he picked up the batteries from since they were a few miles down the road asking if they would take back his load and help up-right the battery that had spilled. They accepted. The police gave the driver permission to drive back to the custmer with the Hazmat clean up team following to make sure that nothing leaked from the trailer during transit. Nothing leaked during the move. The police informed the driver that they will have the trunpike maintenacne clean up the spilled area on the ramp. Once back at the cusomer, the customer unloaded the load and helped to up-right the spilled battery. They are going to re-palletize ALL the batteries and put them on better/ stronger pallets for a future pick up. The Hazmat team cleaned out the trailer and will take care of the clean up waste. Once the trailer was cleaned the driver returned home with an
column169: - The driver was re-trained on packaging and securing used Industrial Motive Power Batteries. An emphasis was on inspecting the condition and the banding to the pallets.  - The customer will be re-issued the visual aid instructions regarding proper packaging and securing of Industrial Motive Power batteries to pallets.

column168: The truck and trailer were traveling East in US 78 in Stone Mountain GA.  The driver then took the W Park Pl Blvd exit and proceeded to turn right onto W Park Pl Blvd.  There is a traffic light at the intersection and the driver had the green light.  As the driver was completing the turn, he felt the trailer shift and when he checked in his mirrors, he observed the trailer rolling over.  The truck did not attempt to roll over and he was able to pull the truck over to the side of the road and stop.  The trailer rolled onto the lift side then top and the right side landed on top of a car waiting at the traffic signal which was red.  There was another car in front of the car it landed on and it struck the rear of the car which was later driven from the scene buy the occupants.  The seam split on the lower left of the tank which did not leak because of the final resting position of the tank, it was at the top above the level of the fuel.  The crack was a direct result of the rollover.  The crack was later enlarged to facilitate the removal of the fuel from that compartment. The rear most top inspection hatch was leaking and the fire department added an additional clamp to the lid to slow the leak and they put a containment pool under the lid to catch the leaking fuel.  The bulkheads between compartments 4, and 5 the comp internally ruptured into the void. Holes were then drilled into the side of the trailer which were facing up and the majority of the fuel was pumped from the trailer while it was on it's side.  The trailer was the righted and the remaining fuel was pumped from the load heads on the bottom of trailer.  The fire department made a small earthen dam to stop the flow of fuel from the small leaks while we were waiting for the Hazmat cleanup companies to arrive.  They then use absorbent material and booms to catch and contain the small leaks.
column169: This accident was caused by a failure of the metal in the hitch.  The metal failed and bent  allowing the upper half of the hitch to come out of the adjustment track and roll over.  The upper half of the hitch was still connected to the trailer and the lower half was still attached to the frame of the truck after the accident.  Our auditor from the DOT James Landrum, P (678) 284-5155 M: (678) 215-5294 james.landrum@dot.gov inspected the truck and trailer as well as both halves of the hitch and stated that this failure could not be predicted by the driver or a mechanic doing routine inspections and service and therefore was an unpreventable accident.  We also had a retired DOT officer and independent DOT consultant Garry Bingham Transportation Compliance, LLC transcomp@charter.net 706 313 6285 look at the hitch and he agreed with James Landrum's assessment.  We inspected all the other trucks and only found 1 with a similar hitch.  The truck was taken out of service until the hitch inspected for any signs of wear and cracking. We have stressed with our drivers the importance of thorough inspections of their hitches and rollover awareness.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Yard crew reported liquid and a strong odor coming from CTCX 733390.  Upon inspection of the car from the ground, the combination housing could be seen resting on the handle of the liquid line valve.  The valve was in the open position.  On top of the car we found the liquid line plug to be out of the valve body and confirmed the valve was in the open position.  The valve was closed and the plug was installed and secured, stopping the release.  The rest of the fittings on the car were also checked and found to be tight with no releases.

On June 28th, a package was found on the belt during the sort that was leaking.  The package had zero indications of containing and hazardous materials inside other than the name of the product Gravista Insecticide.  Upon investigating the package an employee did come into contact with the chemical.  The package was opened and two inner receptacles, each containing approximately 9.5 L were inside with one having leaked.  It is unknown what caused the leak.   After reviewing the SDS this is a UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance, liquid, 9, PGIII shipment since the inner receptacles are more than 5L. The spill was cleaned up and the package was placed into a salvage drum and held at the station pending disposition

X-2023070336, X-2023070459: Package was offered to the spill clean up specialist at our station location in Dothan, AL.  Discovered during AM sort operations, package was seen to wet on outside of fibreboard box indicating leakage from inside. Further inspection found that package contained 4 plastic jugs each containing 3.78L of Alligare Diquat Herbicide (UN 1760) placed in a Surge Broadleaf Herbicide for turf box, UN 3082.  Each set of 2 jugs was placed in a plastic moisture barrier before being placed in the box.  It was seen leakage originated from the caps of the bottles and is believed to have been caused by expansion due to local heat.  SDS of Surge Broardleaf Herbicide shows commodity could travel under special provision A197.  However, the SDS also shows product has a flash point of 57 C and a boiling point of 100 C. Flammable, packing group III.  There are no marks nor labels on the package indicating the product being shipped was flammable.  SDS for Alligare Diquat shows commodity would be classified as UN1760 Corrosive Liquid, N.O.S (contains diquat dibromide) There were no marks nor labels to indicate a corrosive product was being transported.  Package was contained at location and  is awaiting FAA disposition.
